{
  "sectionCode": "10/21",
  "sectionCodeDisplay": "10/21",
  "title": "History and Foundations of Mathematics",
  "outline": [
    {
      "level": "A",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "History of mathematics",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The development of mathematics in general, through ancient, medieval, and modem times",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Ancient and medieval periods",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "Ideas and methods originating or developing in Mesopotamia and Egypt",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Greek and Hellenistic mathematics",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The Middle Ages: Islamic mathematics and its transmission to the West",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The modem period",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "The 17th century: discovery of logarithms and analytic geometry, development of calculus by Newton and Leibniz",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The 18th century: advances in geometry, algebra, and analysis; contributions of the Bernoulli family, Euler, Lagrange, Laplace, and others",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The 19th and 20th centuries: development of non-Euclidean geometry by Bolyai, Lobachevsky, and others; contributions to the theories of groups, functions, and complex variables; development of algebraic geometry; influence of physical science on analysis; study of the foundations of mathematics",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Historical development of representative nonprobabilistic areas of mathematics",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Numerals and numeral systems [see also 10/23.A.1]",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "Simple grouping systems: ancient Egyptian, Babylonian, Greek, and Roman numerals",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Development of multiplicative, ciphered, and positional numeral systems",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Introduction of symbolic notations to represent mathematical quantities, operations, and relationships",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Calculatory science [see also 10/23. A.]",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "The history of mathematical tables, including tables of logarithms",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The evolution of analogue devices: origins of harmonic analyzers, differential analyzers, and the slide rule",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The evolution of digital devices: development of computational aids from the abacus to the modern electronic digital computer [see 10/23.A.7.]",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Geometry [see also 10/22. C.]",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "Egyptian, Babylonian, and Greek geometry",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "The algebraic approach: development of analytic geometry",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Development of projective geometry , iv. Development of non-Euclidean geometry",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "v",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Philosophical aspects of geometry",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "vi",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Modern ideas and topics in geometry: the axiomatic method; geometrical transformations; the concept of space, differential geometry, and topology",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Algebra [see also 10/22. B.]",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "Babylonian, Egyptian, and Greek contributions",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Contributions from the Orient, India, and the Islamic world",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Medieval and modern European developments",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iv",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Evolution of the theory of algebraic equations of one variable: solutions prior to and after Galois",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Historical development of probabilistic areas of mathematics [see also 10/22.D.6.]",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Development of the mathematical theory of probability",
              "children": [
                {
                  "level": "i",
                  "levelType": "lowercase",
                  "text": "The abstract calculus of probability: the common structure of theories of probability",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "ii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Alternative views of probability: the frequency theory of probability, the range theory of probability and the principle of indifference, the belief theory of probability, subjective and objective notions of probability",
                  "children": []
                },
                {
                  "level": "iii",
                  "levelType": "roman",
                  "text": "Bernoulli's theorem, inverse probability, and asymptotic probabilities",
                  "children": []
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Development of mathematical statistics: the history of the theory of stochastic processes, origins of control theory",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "B",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Foundations of mathematics",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The axiomatic method: mathematical analysis based upon a set of axioms, or unproved statements",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Euclidean geometry [see also 10/22.C. 1.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Non-Euclidean geometry [see also 10/22.C.2.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The formal axiomatic method",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The genetic method: mathematical analysis based upon the orderly construction or generation of objects with unknown properties from objects with known properties",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Arithmetic and analysis [see also 10/22.B.1.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The concept of cardinal number and the theory of sets [see also 10/22. A.2.]",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The crisis in the foundations of mathematics after 1900: reformulations in terms of the three alternative philosophical positions of Intuitionism, Logicism, and Formalism",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The paradoxes",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Intuitionism",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Logicism, Formalism, and the metamathematical method",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Current directions in investigations of the foundations of mathematics",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Intuitionistic studies of the foundations of mathematics: application of formalistic procedures to Intuitionism",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
